tasks.description:
Create `src/keychain.rs` with a module-level `//!` doc comment and two crate-private functions (rust-modules.mdc: 'default to minimum visibility'):

```rust
//! macOS Keychain helpers for storing the CompactifAI API key.

/// Reads `MULTIVERSE_IAM_API_KEY` from the macOS Keychain.
///
/// Service: `"yaptap"`, Account: `"MULTIVERSE_IAM_API_KEY"`.
/// Returns `None` if the item does not exist.
pub(crate) fn keychain_get_api_key() -> Option<String>

/// Writes `MULTIVERSE_IAM_API_KEY` to the macOS Keychain.
///
/// Creates the item if absent; updates it if already present.
///
/// # Errors
/// Returns an error if the Keychain operation fails (e.g. user denied access,
/// Keychain locked, or `security-framework` internal error).
pub(crate) fn keychain_set_api_key(key: &str) -> anyhow::Result<()>
```

Use `security_framework::passwords::{get_generic_password, set_generic_password}` (service: `"yaptap"`, account: `"MULTIVERSE_IAM_API_KEY"`).

Both functions must be `unsafe`-free (the `security-framework` crate wraps the C API safely).

Register the module in `src/main.rs` as `mod keychain;`.

Add a `#[cfg(test)] mod tests` block at the bottom of `src/keychain.rs` with a round-trip test (rust-testing.mdc: 'unit tests live in a `#[cfg(test)] mod tests` block'). The test should call `keychain_set_api_key` then `keychain_get_api_key` and assert the stored value matches. Mark it `#[ignore]` with a comment explaining it requires a real Keychain (cannot run in CI without macOS Keychain access).

After parsing the config TOML in `AppConfig::load()`, validate that `llm_provider` is one of the accepted values. If it is not `"ollama"` or `"compactifai"`, fall back to `"ollama"` and push a warning string.

This matches the error case in specs/config.md: "Unknown llm_provider '<value>' — using default: ollama."

The existing hotkey validation at lines 200–211 of `config.rs` is the model to follow: it calls `tracing::warn!`, pushes a message to the `warnings` vector, and resets the field — it does NOT call `show_alert()` directly inside `config.rs`. The caller (`app.rs`) is responsible for iterating the returned `warnings` and showing alerts.

In the same block where unknown `hotkey` values are handled, add:
```rust
if cfg.llm_provider != "ollama" && cfg.llm_provider != "compactifai" {
    let bad = cfg.llm_provider.clone();
    tracing::warn!(value = %bad, "unknown llm_provider — using default: ollama");
    warnings.push(format!(
        "Unknown llm_provider '{bad}' — using default: ollama."
    ));
    cfg.llm_provider = "ollama".to_string();
}
```

The `warnings` vector is already declared earlier in `AppConfig::load()` and returned alongside the config. No changes to `app.rs` are needed — the caller already iterates `warnings` and shows an alert for each entry.
